Certainly! Storing form data on the backend is a crucial step in many web applications. For simplicity, we'll focus on storing the form data in memory using an in-memory storage solution. In a production environment, you would typically use a database like MongoDB, PostgreSQL, or MySQL. However, for this example, we'll use an in-memory storage solution to keep things straightforward.

### Step-by-Step Guide

1. **Set Up the Backend to Store Data in Memory**
2. **Modify the Form Submission Handler to Save Data**

Let's go through each step in detail.

### Step 1: Set Up the Backend to Store Data in Memory

We'll use an array to store the form data temporarily. This array will act as our in-memory database.

#### Update `server.js`

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const bodyParser = require('body-parser');

const app = express();
const PORT = 3000;

// Middleware to parse form data
app.use(bodyParser.urlencoded({ extended: true }));

// In-memory storage for form data
let formData = [];

// Serve static files from the "public" directory
app.use(express.static('public'));

// Route to handle form submission
app.post('/submit-form', (req, res) => {
    const { name, email, message } = req.body;

    // Simple validation (you can expand this)
    if (!name || !email || !message) {
        return res.status(400).send('All fields are required.');
    }

    // Process the form data and store it in memory
    const formDataItem = {
        name,
        email,
        message
    };

    formData.push(formDataItem);

    // Send a confirmation message back to the user
    res.send(`
        <h1>Thank You!</h1>
        <p>Your message has been received:</p>
        <p>Name: ${name}</p>
        <p>Email: ${email}</p>
        <p>Message: ${message}</p>
    `);
});

// Route to display all stored form data
app.get('/form-data', (req, res) => {
    res.send(formData.map(item => `
        <div>
            <p>Name: ${item.name}</p>
            <p>Email: ${item.email}</p>
            <p>Message: ${item.message}</p>
        </div>
    `).join('\n'));
});

// Start the server
app.listen(PORT, () => {
    console.log(`Server is running on http://localhost:${PORT}`);
});
```

### Step 2: Modify the Form Submission Handler to Save Data

The form submission handler already saves the data to the `formData` array. We added a route to display all stored form data at `/form-data`.

### Step 3: Test the Form and View Stored Data

1. **Run the Application**

   ```sh
   node server.js
   ```

2. **Open Your Web Browser**

   Navigate to `http://localhost:3000` to see the form. Fill out the form and submit it. You should receive a confirmation message.

3. **View Stored Data**

   After submitting the form, navigate to `http://localhost:3000/form-data` to see the stored form data displayed in the browser.

### Full Project Structure

Here's what your project directory should look like:

```
simple-form-app/
├── public/
│   └── index.html
├── server.js
└── package.json
```

### `public/index.html`

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Simple Contact Form</title>
</head>
<body>
    <h1>Contact Us</h1>
    <form action="/submit-form" method="post">
        <label for="name">Name:</label>
        <input type="text" id="name" name="name" required><br><br>

        <label for="email">Email:</label>
        <input type="email" id="email" name="email" required><br><br>

        <label for="message">Message:</label>
        <textarea id="message" name="message" rows="4" required></textarea><br><br>

        <input type="submit" value="Submit">
    </form>
</body>
</html>
```

### Running the Application

1. **Start the Server**

   ```sh
   node server.js
   ```

2. **Test the Form**

   Open your web browser and navigate to `http://localhost:3000`. Fill out the form and submit it. You should see a confirmation message.

3. **View Stored Data**

   Navigate to `http://localhost:3000/form-data` to see the stored form data.

### Summary

- **In-Memory Storage**: We used an array to store form data temporarily.
- **Form Submission**: The form data is validated and stored in the `formData` array.
- **Displaying Data**: Added a route to display the stored form data.

This setup gives you a clear understanding of how to capture and store form data on the backend. You can expand this by integrating with a database for persistent storage in a real-world application.

